DAMATURU – Nigeria Association of Women Journalists (NAWOJ), Yobe State chapter, has called on the judiciary to fast track all cases relating to Gender-Based Violence (GBV), abuse and violation against women’s rights in Yobe State with a view to ensuring proper justice and prosecution of offenders without further delay. Fatima Mohammed Ahmad, Chairperson of NAWOJ, Yobe State chapter, made the plea in a statement made available to DAILY INDEPENDENT in Damaturu on Wednesday in continuation of the celebration of International Women’s Day. She said, “NAWOJ Yobe State wants to reiterate that our women are not second class citizens whose responsibility is limited to household chores but rather a specifically made precious creature of God that is designed to handle multi-task of nation building.” HOW NIGERIAN MEN CAN NOW NATURALLY STOP PREMATURE EJACULATION, LOW SPERM COUNT AND OTHER MEN'S SEXUAL NEEDS. MADAM ALWAYS WANTS IT BIGGER, STRONGER AND LONG-LASTING!!! She added: “Hence, on this day NAWOJ urges all Men especially husbands to acknowledge the worth and significance of Women in their lives and their tremendous contributions to the family and society”. The NAWOJ Chairperson further disclosed that celebrating Women is a sense of obligation to every Woman in ones life. Nigeria’s Future Lies In Her Youth, Revd Pam Tells YOWICAN Labour Threatens Shut Down Of Economy | TV Independent This year she said, NAWOJ Yobe State chapter is joining the World to amplify voice and advocacy for more Women inclusiveness in government and decision making positions. While commending Yobe State Governor Mai Mala Buni for providing a matching ladder for Women politicians in Yobe State which resulted in the emergence of a Chairlady of Fika Local Government Council, Hajiya Halima Kyari Joda and several female councillors and supervisory councillors in the just concluded local government elections.